The CZ P-07 is the updated version of the CZ 75 P-07 Duty. The debut of the full-size P-09 last year brought refined lines and interchangeable backstraps to our polymer Omega line. This year the compact-sized P-07 follows suit, with new features and a nitrated slide finish that wears longer and has increased corrosion resistance. The pistol as a whole has been dehorned, removing any sharp edges to make it more comfortable for all-day carry.

Like the P-09, the P-07’s safety and decocker are interchangeable with a few minutes and minimal tools. Add to that small, medium and large backstraps and an integrated 1913 Picatinny rail on the dust cover and the P-07 is adaptable to the shooter and their needs, from service pistol to bedside protector to the envy of the shooting range.

The P-07 shares the P-09’s updated trigger shape which is more comfortable for long days at the range, as well as its snag-free hammer and forward cocking serrations. Metal 3-dot sights and a beefed up magazine spring round out the bevy of updates, resulting in the best P-07 we’ve had to date.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger Flat Top .44 magnun 1962 Blackhawk / Pre Super Blackhawk - Free Shipping
postcontent:
LAST WEEK BEFORE LEAVING MONTANA
Old Smoke is a retired hand carried many years on an Arizona ranch as a working sidearm. Definitely a cowboy gun. I have owned this neat old piece for several years and am simply downsizing my collection. I have a Super Blackhawk 3-screw and that's enough.
This Ruger .44-magnum Blackhawk was manufactured in 1962 and has the 6-1/2" barrel of that time. It's the Blackhawk designation since the Super Blackhawk was not yet in existence. It wears an earned patina finish, I've never been able to bring myself to send it off to Ruger to re-blue for several reasons. 
First, once it's done, it's done
My other reason is, this fine revolver came by the patina finish with age and regular carry. Besides, Uberti charges extra money for their "Antique" washed finish. A re-blue should be decided by the next owner.
I have never came across an old Three Screw with this kind of seasoned wear without seeing pitting or worse. There is no pitting on this revolver. 
The timing is excellent with only the faintest turn ring on the cylinder, a testament to Ruger's fine craftsmanship of the day. 
Lock-up it strong and tight with no cylinder play.
Bore and cylinders are in fine shape with plenty of lands and grooves. It's obvious that it was worn in a holster but must have been wiped down regularly 
Certainly not worn out from shooting. I have no way of knowing how many rounds have been fired through it, but I've never seen one worn out from shooting. 
Included is the old vintage Hunter holster Old Smoke rode in for decades. This revolver also has a set of vintage Jay Scott faux stag grips of the period. There is no box or original grips. It shoots true and will get the job done every time.
Price: $690.00 
Type of Payment: United States Post Office Money Order. However, If the buyer calls me, I may accept a personal check with an agreed upon understanding that the revolver will not be shipped until the buyers check has cleared my bank. That can take up to ten-days.
Shipping: $20.00 
Plenty more pictures on request.

postcontent:
For sale is a group of WWII era rifles that are in excellent condition.  This part of an estate sale and everything must go! Listed in order:

1. Swiss K-31 straight- pull rifle with original sling and bayonet w/ scabbard.  All numbers matching. The bluing on this rifle is awesome and the shield on top of the receiver is flawless.  Rare Beech wood stock instead of the common Walnut, 7.5 Swiss. Nice find with the original sling and bayonet.  $475

2. Swiss K-1911 straight-pull long rifle. All numbers matching.  Has detachable magazine.  Great bore and stock.  7.5 Swiss.  This rifle doesn't have a Swiss seal on the top of the receiver because the production year pre-dates when the Swiss started stamping that on (19 teens). $400

3. Chinese M-21 7.62x39mm with original sling.  Wood and metal in great condition, and has a tight bore. All numbers matching and has the spike bayonet.  Has the factory plastic hand guard known as the "french tickler" hand guard.  These M-21 versions are getting tougher to find in this nice of condition. $450

4. Chinese Type 56 SKS 7.62x39mm with original sling.  Very good condition, very few scratches or handling marks.  All numbers matching and comes with the spike bayonet.  Has the factory plastic hand guard known as the "french tickler" hand guard. According to a serial number look up, this rifle was manufactured in the mid 1970s. $400

5. Japanese Type 44 Carbine. 6.5 Arisaka. Now this one is RARE.  Great stock and bolt.  Bore appears to be shiny with lots of life. Attached bayonet.  Functions flawlessly. $825

6. Japanese Type 38 Carbine. 6.5 Arisaka.  All numbers matching, has cleaning rod, full mum in perfect condition, matching dust cover, and original sling.  Great condition cosmetically and mechanically.  These are getting tougher to find. $725

7. Japanese Type 99 with the original sling.  7.7 Arisaka.  Great condition and tight bore. Has mum and cleaning rod.  Bayonet w/ scabbard is available. This is a nice find with the cleaning rod, sling, and bayonet. A must have. $500 or $600 with bayonet.

Quality is deep in this group.  Don't miss you opportunity to own a piece of history.  Call/text REDACTED

title: For Sale:  **Threaded Contender barrel**
postcontent:
I have a Thompson Center Contender barrel chambered in 223. It is a hard to find "Super 16" (see pictures), most 223 Contender barrels are "Super 14" and this one includes the iron sights. The bore is immaculate. This barrel also has the muzzle threaded 1/2-28 for a silencer or flash hider or muzzle brake. The barrel was threaded concentric to the bore using the single point method on a lathe, NOT threaded using a die. This ensures the threads are perfectly concentric to the bore and 100% safe with a silencer. I have tested it with my silencer and it works perfectly. Because it is a single shot it will also make the 223 as quiet as it could possibly be. The factory front sight was moved back to accommodate the threaded muzzle. An 11 degree target crown was added to ensure the barrel is very accurate, both with and without a silencer. It will include the Weaver scope mount that was on it when I bought the barrel. The iron sights are the finger adjustable type so no tools are needed to make adjustments. The barrel also has the very desirable dual locking lugs which ensures a tight lockup as well as being extremely easy to open. The dimple in the threads is from the old front sight screw hole and does not affect the barrel, threads or function at all. It includes a rifle forearm in walnut and the two screws to attach it to the barrel.

 This is an amazing deal because the "Super 16" barrels are getting extremely hard to find, especially the 223 with iron sights, and when you do expect to pay $250+. The cost of threading will cost $75+ not including shipping and to move the factory sights back expect to pay another $50. The scope mount is another $20. Most places charge ~$50 to put an 11 degree target crown on a barrel.

 And because it is chambered in 223 it is extremely cheap to shoot. And because it is 16" you can add a folding stock for the ultimate survival rig. With a Choate folding stock the gun will be 21" folded making for a great backpack or survival gun.

 I am so confident in this price that if you can find this setup cheaper PM me the links and I will match that price.

 Price for barrel is $325 shipped. I can take PayPal or postal money order, no personal or bank checks. Will take AK and Glock magazines or accessories. Not interested in any Contender or Encore trades.

 I am selling because I am getting out of 223/5.56 because I rarely shoot the caliber any more.
